english:
  title: Record of the Reconstruction of the Guest House at Hanzhou
  author: Lee Gok
  language: eng
  text: "In the autumn of the year Gichuk of the Zhizheng era, heavy rains fell and the south corridor of the guest house at Masan collapsed. When the rains ceased and the harvest season drew to a close, the people of the district wished to repair it. The provincial governor Park said, \"Why repair only the south corridor? The main hall and covered walkways are nearly ruined as well. Should we not rebuild all of it anew?\" The people replied, \"Our land produces no timber. Even an eight-foot log must be brought from mountains a hundred li distant. Moreover, most of our people are under the thumb of the powerful—who would consent to labor for us?\" \n\nThe governor said, \"Why hesitate? It shall be done.\" Then he added, \"If we do not tear down the old buildings, the people will lack the will to work.\" And so in a single day, everything was razed. The people grew fearful and anxious. The governor then assessed the talents of his officials—those of ability he entrusted with larger buildings and more workers; those less skilled received less. Having thus divided the tasks, he addressed them: \"The ancients said, 'When the ruler employs the people with ease, even labor brings no resentment.' All that you eat and wear upon this soil, all that spares you from despair, comes from the grace of your superiors. When guests arrive, we proclaim the virtue of the Son of Heaven or disseminate the kingdom's edicts—all for the welfare of the realm's foundation. This guest house exists for the people. Is not this labor a way to bring you ease? Moreover, the old buildings are shabby and crumbling, unfit to receive emissaries or hear imperial proclamations. I fear only dishonoring my post. Let none dare neglect or disobey—punishment awaits the transgressor.\"\n\nThereupon, households were assessed for workers, excepting only the elderly and children. Men crossed the sea to fetch timber, undeterred by hardship and distance. Contributions poured in; provisions were brought so abundantly that carriers brushed shoulders. Work began in the intercalary month of that year, and within mere weeks the halls and galleries rose complete. But winter came with freezing cold, making plastering impossible, so work was suspended until spring of the following year. By the second month, completion drew near—neither grand nor humble, suited to the landscape; neither extravagant nor mean, fitting the times. Those who had begun in doubt now rejoiced and marveled. Even the formerly proud and willful now obediently followed orders.\n\nIt was determined that official buildings and libraries must also be constructed, and plans were drawn. But Governor Park was transferred away. The people were lost, as though orphaned. Truly, Park was gifted. I, raised in these hills, know that a people's fortune depends upon their magistrate. In our region, I have seen this proven. While at court, I heard that our officials and people often fled and hid, that thorns grew upon our roads and travelers found no shelter, that magistrates knew not what to do and departed bearing their seals. I sighed and said, \"This is not the fault of officials and people alone—those entrusted with the land cannot escape their responsibility.\"\n\nIn the spring of the year Byungsu, returning with imperial proclamations, I found that Governor Lee Cha had begun his tenure. He ordered his officials with method and governed the people with law. All the region marveled at the results appearing within half a year. Yet before six months had passed, he was summoned to court. Governor Lee Jajang succeeded him, advancing the work with greater diligence, accomplishing all he undertook. He declared, \"Imperial law calls the magistrate's residence the Public Hall. Our governor dwells in private homes—how can this be? How can there be a district?\" He commanded his officials to divide the tasks, and in days the work was done. He began the sequential repair of all guest facilities, but soon family affliction called him away.\n\nWhen Governor Park arrived, he united the talents of both Lees. In but a few years, benefit flourished and harm vanished. The work was accomplished, the people harmonized. Truly, this was not the Hanzhou of old. Moreover, he treated all with sincerity and received guests with unfailing courtesy. In provisions, bedding, and furnishings both great and small, all was complete and spotless. Yet he drew upon the public treasury and confiscated wealth—not a single coin extracted from the people. Thus his reputation blossomed and surpassed all in the region.\n\nI, a native here, in the leisure of filial service, have been fortunate to witness these events. Now, with the completion of the guest house, I record this account. Alas, may those who follow Governor Park take him as their model, and complete what remains unfinished! Then need we not fear the want of capable magistrates. Governor Park's name is Siyong, his courtesy name is Dobu, and he is of the Milseong clan. Having risen through examination, he served in the civil service, was appointed Inspector General, and by established custom came forth as a provincial governor. I record this in the third month of the year Gyeongin."
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Zhizheng era: The reign period of the Mongol Yuan Dynasty (1341-1368). The year Gichuk would be 1349, placing this narrative in the late Yuan period when Korean territories were under Mongol influence.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Park: A reference to Governor Park Si-yong (朴時庸), whose administration exemplified capable and ethical governance.'
  - key: ''
    value: The contrast between Park and his predecessors illustrates the Confucian principle that administrative virtue flows from the magistrate and transforms the people.
  - key: ''
    value: The guest house (gaeksa/客舍) served diplomatic and administrative functions, receiving imperial messengers and promulgating royal edicts—hence its importance to the state.
  - key: ''
    value: 'The author''s meditation on magistrate virtue reflects core Confucian political philosophy: a capable, ethical administrator naturally earns the people''s cooperation without coercion.'
